{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502599","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502599"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:47:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1879"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1879"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.27,0.23,0.2,0.18,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44104"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1879","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1879"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1879"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29081"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1788"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34150"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44104"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 86-year-old man presents to his General Practitioner after an episode of left sided abdominal pain the previous day, which resolved spontaneously after several hours. He has no other symptoms. His medical history includes a laparoscopic cholecystectomy 10 years earlier and a colonoscopy for diverticulitis five years ago. He takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well and vitals are all within normal limits. On abdominal examination the patient has a soft abdomen, with no masses. An abdominal CT scan is ordered (Images 1 - 2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following does the CT scan show?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["A normal examination","Renal neoplasm","Para-oesophageal hernia","Choledocholithiasis","Gastric tumour"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT scan was probably undertaken because the general practitioner was concerned that the recent episode of left sided abdominal pain could have been related to the patient\u0027s known diverticular disease. Of the parts of the colon that are visible in the two sections, there is no evidence of diverticular disease - but the sigmoid colon (the usual site) is not shown. What is evident is a stone which can be seen towards the distal end of a dilated common bile duct - see the arrows (Images 1 - 2). In this case the \u003Cstrong\u003Echoledocholithiasis\u003C/strong\u003E is almost certainly an incidental finding. Perhaps less so with common duct stones, but incidental findings on imaging are relatively common and it has been estimated that more that 50% of patients who have an abdominal CT scan in the Emergency Department will have such findings. More common examples include renal cysts, liver lesions, diverticular disease and gallstones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuct stones are found in about 15% of patients with gallbladder stones. They are usually asymptomatic. This stone might have been present at the time of the original cholecystectomy - or formed subsequently. The risks of potential complications (cholangitis, pancreatitis) must now be weighed up the risks of endoscopic stone removal (bleeding, perforation, pancreatitis). There is no absolute answer, but in the older patient, a good argument can be made for leaving things alone - primum non nocere.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth kidneys are well defined and there is no evidence of a\u003Cstrong\u003E renal neoplasm\u003C/strong\u003E. The gastric fundus can be seen on the coronal view and there is no evidence of a \u003Cstrong\u003Egastric tumour\u003C/strong\u003E or \u003Cstrong\u003Epara-oesophageal hernia\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Incidental radiological findings are commonplace and usually of no clinical significance."],"references":["Thompson RJ,  Wojcik SM, Grant WD, et al. Incidental Findings on CT Scans in the Emergency Department. Emerg Med Int. 2011;10.1155. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22046542/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29081"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1879"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16980"},{"type":"media","id":"16981"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"16982"},{"type":"media","id":"16983"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"16980","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16980"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f1e1d7f1-b8c8-4d02-b5ed-fb64e883d468.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/f1e1d7f1-b8c8-4d02-b5ed-fb64e883d468.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":549,"height":456}},{"type":"media","id":"16981","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16981"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8899d71e-3955-4380-b9ba-54373e853bcc.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/8899d71e-3955-4380-b9ba-54373e853bcc.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":626,"height":599}},{"type":"media","id":"16982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/16982"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bd6a50d5-0a66-4f6c-ab1e-d43327615f1e.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/bd6a50d5-0a66-4f6c-ab1e-d43327615f1e.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":485,"height":419}},{"type":"media","id":"16983","lin